The best time for reliability test planning is early in the product development phase, ideally during the design or initial planning stages. This is because reliability considerations need to be integrated into the design itself—decisions about materials, components, architecture, and manufacturing processes all impact reliability, and once these are locked in, it becomes much harder and more costly to make changes later. Planning reliability tests early allows for defining reliability goals, selecting appropriate tests (like accelerated life tests or HALT), and ensuring testing resources are available. While planning can still occur before production, the most effective approach is to start as early as possible to influence design choices and prevent reliability issues from arising.

